   "source": [
    "### **Building GPT-2**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "82ea1443",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### **GPTConfig**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "cbe82d3b",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from dataclasses import dataclass\n",
    "import torch \n",
    "import torch.nn as nn \n",
    "from torch.nn import functional as F \n",
    "import inspect\n",
    "\n",
    "# decorator makes GPTConfig as a datalclass \n",
    "# this class exists to purely bundle together the hyperparameters that define the model's shape/size\n",
    "# the @dataclass enables variable access and auto-generates an __init__ method behind the scenes \n",
    "@dataclass\n",
    "class GPTConfig: \n",
    "    block_size: int = 1024 # maximum sequence length (context window)\n",
    "    vocab_size: int = 50257 # number of unique tokens\n",
    "    n_layer: int = 12 # number of transformr blocks stacked on top of each other\n",
    "    n_head: int = 12 # number of parallel attention heads within each transformer block's multi-head self-attention\n",
    "    n_embd: int = 768 # dimensionality of embedding vectors"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "fc92bcaf",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "- `GPTConfig` essentially serves as the class that stores all the hyperparameter attributes that we will continuously use throughout the transformer\n",
    "\n",
    "- We pass `GPTConfig` object when calling other classes so they have access to these parameters stored in a single location"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "daf8cf49",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### **Transformer Block**\n",
    "\n",
    "(× n_layer, e.g. 12 for GPT-2 124M -> repeat 12 loops of the block):\n",
    "\n",
    "<pre>\n",
    "x\n",
    "│\n",
    "├──> LayerNorm (ln_1)\n",
    "│        │\n",
    "│        ▼\n",
    "│   Masked Multi-Head Self-Attention\n",
    "│        │\n",
    "▼        ▼\n",
    "└──────(+)──── residual add #1\n",
    "         │\n",
    "         x  (updated)\n",
    "         │\n",
    "         ├──> LayerNorm (ln_2)\n",
    "         │        │\n",
    "         │        ▼\n",
    "         │      MLP / Feedforward\n",
    "         │        │\n",
    "         ▼        ▼\n",
    "         └──────(+)──── residual add #2\n",
    "                  │\n",
    "                  ▼\n",
    "               output x (→ next block)\n",
    "<pre>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5b7997a0",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "##### **Multi-Headed Masked Self-Attention**\n",
    "- Applied to help tokens communicate with one another — each token can look at and pull information from other tokens, rather than being processed in isolation\n",
    "\n",
    "- Specifically *masked* (causal) — a token can only communicate with previous tokens, not future ones\n",
    "\n",
    "- This is what transforms the raw data relationship (1 token predicts the next, per the shifted x/y labels) into all previous tokens becoming the context used to predict the next token\n",
    "\n",
    "- \"Multi-headed\" = this happens in parallel across several independent heads, each computing its own affinities/context, later mixed together via a linear projection"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "bdc2d440",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class CausalSelfAttention(nn.Module):\n",
    "    def __init__(self, config):\n",
    "        super().__init__()\n",
    " \n",
    "        # n_embd must divide evenly across all heads, otherwise concatenating\n",
    "        # the heads back together at the end won't reconstruct n_embd exactly\n",
    "        assert config.n_embd % config.n_head == 0\n",
    " \n",
    "         # key, query, value projections for all heads, but in a batch\n",
    "        self.n_head = config.n_head\n",
    "        self.n_embd = config.n_embd\n",
    "        self.head_size = config.n_embd // config.n_head  # size of each individual head's q/k/v vectors\n",
    " \n",
    "        # NOTE: unlike a naive \"one small nn.Linear per head\" implementation, we instead\n",
    "        # project all the way to the FULL n_embd size ONCE for each of key/query/value.\n",
    "        # We then reshape (split) that single n_embd-sized output into n_head separate\n",
    "        # chunks of size head_size later in forward(). This is mathematically equivalent\n",
    "        # to having n_head separate small linear layers, but is done as one big matrix\n",
    "        # multiply per q/k/v for efficiency (fewer, larger ops instead of many small ones).\n",
    "        self.key = nn.Linear(config.n_embd, config.n_embd)\n",
    "        self.query = nn.Linear(config.n_embd, config.n_embd)\n",
    "        self.value = nn.Linear(config.n_embd, config.n_embd)\n",
    " \n",
    "        # output projection: mixes information ACROSS heads after they've been computed independently and concatenated back together. Shape is already n_embd -> n_embd\n",
    "        self.proj = nn.Linear(config.n_embd, config.n_embd)\n",
    "        self.proj.NANOGPT_SCALE_INIT = 1 # attaching an extra attribute\n",
    "\n",
    "        # causal mask: a lower-triangular matrix of 1s and 0s, built ONCE at the maximum possible sequence length (block_size). 1 = \"allowed to attend to this position\",\n",
    "        # 0 = \"this is a future position, must be masked out\". Stored as a buffer (not a parameter since it remains constant)\n",
    "        self.register_buffer(\"bias\", torch.tril(torch.ones(config.block_size, config.block_size)).view(1, 1, config.block_size, config.block_size)\n",
    "            # shape (1, 1, block_size, block_size) -- the two leading 1-dims are for\n",
    "            # (batch, n_head), which will broadcast correctly against att's real\n",
    "            # (B, n_head, T, T) shape without needing to be repeated per-batch/per-head\n",
    "        )\n",
    " \n",
    "    def forward(self, x):\n",
    "        # x.shape = (B, T, C) = (no.examples, block_size_used, n_embd)\n",
    "        B, T, C = x.shape\n",
    " \n",
    "        # apply linear projections to x to get the full-size key, query and value matrices\n",
    "        k = self.key(x)    # k.shape = (B, T, n_embd)\n",
    "        q = self.query(x)  # q.shape = (B, T, n_embd)\n",
    "        v = self.value(x)  # v.shape = (B, T, n_embd)\n",
    " \n",
    "        # split the last dimension (n_embd) into (n_head, head_size), then move n_head into the batch-like dimension via transpose so that matrix multiplication treats each head completely independently.\n",
    "        # .view(...): (B, T, n_embd) -> (B, T, n_head, head_size)\n",
    "        # .transpose(1, 2): (B, T, n_head, head_size) -> (B, n_head, T, head_size)\n",
    "        k = k.view(B, T, self.n_head, self.head_size).transpose(1, 2)\n",
    "        q = q.view(B, T, self.n_head, self.head_size).transpose(1, 2)\n",
    "        v = v.view(B, T, self.n_head, self.head_size).transpose(1, 2)\n",
    "        # PyTorch has a trick that treats every dim except for the last 2 as batch dimensions \n",
    "        # batch dimensions are dimensions that do not engage in actual dot-products, they are structural and tell PyTorch \"here are the independent slots to loop over\"\n",
    "        # by reshaping, we let (T, head_size) be the last 2 dimensions \n",
    "        # when we perform a matrx multiplication we are left with (T, T) as the last 2 dimensions \n",
    "        # this is exactly what we want because our affinity scores should represent affinity between tokens in a sequence of length T \n",
    "        # (T can equal up to batch_size but may be less depending on how much context the model needs to generate a reasonable response)\n",
    "\n",
    " \n",
    "        # compute raw attention scores (\"affinities\") between every position's query and every position's key, independently within each head.\n",
    "        # q: (B, n_head, T, head_size) @ k.transpose(-2, -1): (B, n_head, head_size, T)\n",
    "        # -> att: (B, n_head, T, T) \n",
    "        # scaling by 1/sqrt(head_size) to make scores smaller and prevent softmax product from being one_hot encoded - as values are larger they approach one_hot encoding when softmaxed\n",
    "        \"att = (q @ k.transpose(-2, -1)) * (self.head_size ** -0.5)\"\n",
    " \n",
    "        # apply the causal mask: slice self.bias down to the ACTUAL sequence length T (not block_size), since T is often smaller than block_size \n",
    "        # self.bias[:, :, :T, :T] == 0 slices the (block_size, block_size) grid to the required size (T, T) that is used in the actual context window and checks for 0's, then mask_fills over with -inf\n",
    "        # After softmax, -inf becomes exactly 0 probability -- this is what physically prevents any position from attending to future tokens, which is required for valid autoregressive (next-token-prediction) generation.\n",
    "        \"att = att.masked_fill(self.bias[:, :, :T, :T] == 0, float('-inf'))\"\n",
    " \n",
    "        # convert raw masked scores into an actual probability distribution over positions\n",
    "        # to attend to, for each query position independently. dim=-1 applies softmax\n",
    "        # across the \"keys\" dimension (the last T), so each row of att sums to 1.\n",
    "        \"att = F.softmax(att, dim=-1)\" # (B, n_head, T, T)\n",
    " \n",
    "        # weighted sum of value vectors, weighted by attention probabilities.\n",
    "        # att: (B, n_head, T, T) @ v: (B, n_head, T, head_size) -> y: (B, n_head, T, head_size)\n",
    "        \"y = att @ v\"\n",
    "\n",
    "        \"Flash Attention Shortcut\"\n",
    "        # Flash Attention computes the exact same softmax(QK^T/sqrt(d))V result as the manual implementation above, but restructures the computation into tiles processed via a fused GPU kernel, using a running-softmax trick so the full (T,T) attention matrix is never fully materialized in slow VRAM.\n",
    "        # This eliminates the memory read/write bottleneck of the standard approach (which is the real limiting factor, not raw compute), making it significantly faster and more memory-efficient without changing the mathematical output at all.\n",
    "        # The math is identical, what changes is purely the computational strategy for executing that math on the GPU - specifically how data moves between fast on-chip memory and slower VRAM during the calculation\n",
    "        y = F.scaled_dot_product_attention(q, k, v, is_causal=True)\n",
    " \n",
    "        # recombine all heads back into a single n_embd-sized vector per position.\n",
    "        # .transpose(1, 2): (B, n_head, T, head_size) -> (B, T, n_head, head_size)\n",
    "        # .contiguous(): required after transpose, since transpose only changes strides/view metadata without physically rearranging memory -- .view() afterward requires a contiguous memory layout to work correctly\n",
    "        # .view(B, T, C): (B, T, n_head, head_size) -> (B, T, n_embd)\n",
    "        #                 (n_head * head_size reconstructs n_embd exactly, by construction which is the required shape and dim)\n",
    "        y = y.transpose(1, 2).contiguous().view(B, T, C)\n",
    " \n",
    "        # final output projection: mixes information across the (currently independent, just-concatenated) heads together into a genuinely blended representation.\n",
    "        y = self.proj(y)\n",
    " \n",
    "        return y"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "201041a8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "- Linear projection applied to input `x` (last dim remains `n_embd`), producing K, Q, V vectors for attention via a transformation\n",
    "\n",
    "- To apply multi-headed self-attention more efficiently, rather than separately performing successive matrix multiplications and concatenating heads together, we can create another dimension. Previously we split `n_embd` into smaller head_size and then concatenated results but this time we can think of it as splitting up a `n_embd` dimension vector into a 2D tensor of shape `(n_head, head_size)` such that each embedding is now a matrix instead of a vector\n",
    "\n",
    "- We then transpose the matrix via `.transpose(1, 2)` to swtich the second and third dimensions producing (B, n_head, T, head_size). Before this transpose, the data is organized per-token: each token has its own small matrix holding all the heads. After the transpose, this organises the data per-head: each head has its own matrix holding that head's slice across all T tokens, regrouping the same numbers by head instead of by token, so that each head's `T × head_size` matrix is isolated and can be matrix-multiplied independently of the others.\n",
    "\n",
    "- Now, we matrix multiply `Q @ K.transpose(-1, -2)` - switching the last 2 dimensions of K so the dimensions match - producing a (B, n_head, T, T) matrix of attention scores. Since attention scores should represent how tokens are related to one another in the sequence of block_size T, a TxT matrix would represent how each token in the T-long sequence is related to one another. Transposing moves `n_head` into a \"batch-like\" dimension, leaving `B` and `n_head` as purely **structural dimensions** (no dot products happen between them — they're just independent slots PyTorch loops over), while the actual matrix multiplication `(T, head_size) @ (head_size, T)` happens independently per batch item and per head to produce a `(T, T)` matrix as the dot product between `Q` and `K` - shows the **affinities** between tokens\n",
    "\n",
    "- At position `(a, b)` in this scores matrix, this shows the affinity score of query position `a` attending to key position `b` — i.e., how relevant token `b` is to token `a`'s prediction. \n",
    "  - **Row a's values = context used to predict y[a]** (a = index of row)\n",
    "  - This means the masked triangular matrix can be visualised as an accumulation of an increasing context window to predict the next token\n",
    "\n",
    "- Scale this down (dividing by `sqrt(head_size)`) so that when softmaxed, the scores don't approach one-hot encoding — as values get larger, softmax output approaches one-hot, which we want to avoid.\n",
    "\n",
    "- To convert it to a causal matrix of attention scores, we mask it so that it's a lower triangle, meaning each position can only see previous tokens as context (not future ones). \n",
    "  - `att = att.masked_fill(self.bias[:, :, :T, :T] == 0, float('-inf'))`\n",
    "  - `self.bias` (the mask) is one big fixed grid built once at `block_size`, and each forward pass just crops it to the required `T × T` size since the block_size can be a **maximum** length of T but could be less depending on how much context a generation requires\n",
    "\n",
    "- Apply softmax to convert these masked scores into weightings that sum to 1 — this shows how important each token is compared to the other tokens.\n",
    "\n",
    "- Apply these weightings to V (a linear projection applied to input `x` to generate a matrix that represents the information that will be distributed to other heads - adjusted in backpropagation), then apply a projection to mix information across heads.\n",
    "  - Key point: we had one entire matrix, split it into different batch dimensions to deal with the multi-heads in self-attention, reshaped to perform matrix multiplications and output a `T × T` matrix of attention scores (leaving the rest as structural batch dimensions), then reshaped back to a single 3D tensor (from 4D). This final reshaping process however involves concatenation of heads side-by-side as we concatenate on the last dim by `.view()` to the required shape. This isolates each individual head's information and as such we must apply a linear projection to mix information across heads\n",
    "\n",
    "- Now we have a matrix `y` which residually adds all the information from self-attention back onto the values of `x`.\n",
    "\n",
    "- Purely in terms of raw `x` and `y` data (before attention is even considered): `y` is `x` shifted by 1 index, which by itself implies a 1-character-predicts-the-next relationship — character-by-character prediction, nothing more.\n",
    "  - With the implementation of self-attention, tokens can communicate with one another, but only previous characters can be used as context (due to the mask).\n",
    "\n",
    "  - This transforms it from a \"1 character predicts the next\" scenario into \"all previous characters becoming the context window that predicts the next.\"\n",
    "  - The output of self-attention is the relationship between tokens (the affinities/gathered context) — this is fed into the residual stream (added to the input x), which is what actually carries and implements this information in practice, across the depth of the network \n",
    "\n",
    "- **The self-attention class creates the matrix of affinities and applies them to our inputs, the residual stream carries this result and implements it in practice, allowing the tokens to communicate with each other and use all previous tokens to predict the next**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "48bd8796",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "##### **MLP / Feedforward**\n",
    "- Operates on each position **independently** — no cross-token mixing happens here at all (unlike attention, which is the only place tokens communicate with each other)\n",
    "\n",
    "- Structure: Linear (expand `n_embd → 4*n_embd`) → GELU (nonlinearity) → Linear (project back down `4*n_embd → n_embd`)\n",
    "\n",
    "- Expanding to `4*n_embd` gives the model more room to compute in a higher-dimensional space before compressing back down\n",
    "- The second linear layer serves two purposes: fixes the shape back to `n_embd` (so it can be added to the residual stream) *and* combines/compresses the expanded features into a final representation\n",
    "- Why it's needed alongside attention: attention mixes information *across* tokens but has no nonlinear processing of its own; the MLP does the actual \"thinking\"/processing of whatever context attention just gathered, per token\n",
    "- Attention without an MLP = just repeatedly mixing information around with no nonlinear transformation of it; MLP without attention = processing each token in isolation with no context — need both, alternating, to build up richer representations across depth\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "6e4d7b5b",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class MLP(nn.Module):\n",
    "    def __init__(self, config):\n",
    "        super().__init__()\n",
    "        # define the layers we want to implement int he MLP portion of the block \n",
    "        self.c_fc = nn.Linear(config.n_embd, 4 * config.n_embd)\n",
    "        self.gelu = nn.GELU(approximate='tanh') # gelu is just a relu that does not have a flat tail - gets rid of the dead neuron problem\n",
    "        self.proj = nn.Linear(4 * config.n_embd, config.n_embd) # this projection is what transforms the output back to the original shape (B, T, C) to allow for residual addition\n",
    "\n",
    "        self.proj.NANOGPT_SCALE_INIT = 1 # attaching an extra attribute\n",
    "\n",
    "    \n",
    "    def forward(self, x):\n",
    "        # implement the MLP as x flows through it\n",
    "        # x passes through each individual layer, reassigns the value to x, and returns the final x \n",
    "        x = self.c_fc(x) # applies the initial linear transformation\n",
    "        x = self.gelu(x) # applies non-linearity\n",
    "        x = self.proj(x) # projects to the required shape for the residual add\n",
    "        return x"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d9711cd7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "##### **Block Combined**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "3f8272a9",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class Block(nn.Module):\n",
    "    \n",
    "    def __init__(self, config):\n",
    "        super().__init__()\n",
    "\n",
    "        # layernorm\n",
    "        # Keeps each token's value consistent and controlled (gaussian) at every layer, preventing the scale drift across depth that would cause softmax saturation and vanishing/exploding gradients\n",
    "        self.ln_1 = nn.LayerNorm(config.n_embd) # passing n_embd = normalise over the last dim of size n_embd = normalise across columns = normalise rows (hence layerNorm)\n",
    "                                                # must always normalise the last dim (and can normalise more dims in addition to the last dim)\n",
    "        # Self-attention\n",
    "        # Enables tokens to communicate with one another\n",
    "        self.attn = CausalSelfAttention(config) # different object separate for attention itself\n",
    "        # layernorm\n",
    "        self.ln_2 = nn.LayerNorm(config.n_embd) # second layernorm \n",
    "        # MLP/FNN\n",
    "        # Takes what attention gathered (cross-token context) and processes it further, per token (no more cross-token mixing), via mathematical computations\n",
    "        self.mlp = MLP(config) # different object separate for MLP\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # in a single forward pass of the loop perform the following layers in order: layernorm -> attention -> residual add -> layer norm -> feedforward -> residual add\n",
    "    def forward(self, x):\n",
    "        # residual addition (accumulated into x so the final output contains all oeprations from the transformer block)\n",
    "        # replicates the operation flow from layernorm -> attention -> layernorm -> MLP, implementing residual additions along the way that are performed twice\n",
    "        # residual stream x is just the accumulation of the outputs with the original x input\n",
    "        x = x + self.attn(self.ln_1(x)) # x goes through layernorm then attention - residual add after attention so accumulate\n",
    "        x = x + self.mlp(self.ln_2(x)) # the output then goes through another layernorm, then feedforward - residual add after MLP so accumulate\n",
    "        return x"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2404d253",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### **GPT Model - Combining Everything**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "c6debe41",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class GPT(nn.Module):\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __init__(self, config):\n",
    "        super().__init__()\n",
    "\n",
    "        # GPT will pass GPTConfig as config and then instantiate an object config as self.config\n",
    "        # stores the object config as an attribute of the model so it perists beyond just the __init__ call\n",
    "        self.config = config\n",
    "\n",
    "        # access the passed object config's parameters to get the required hyoerparameters for our transformer\n",
    "        # save each of these modules which define the layers of the transformer into a ModuleDict\n",
    "        # ModuleDict allows us to save the modules and allow us to access their submodules (e.g. .paraeters(), etc.)\n",
    "        # ModuleDict expects a dictionary mapping of name:module pairs so we must dict() the entire thing\n",
    "        self.transformer = nn.ModuleDict(dict(\n",
    "            # word token embedding (embedding word tokens to vectors)\n",
    "            wte = nn.Embedding(config.vocab_size, config.n_embd), # key=value is another way to setup a dict using dict() \n",
    "            # word position embedding (embedding position of word to vectors)\n",
    "            wpe = nn.Embedding(config.block_size, config.n_embd),\n",
    "            # stack of transformer blocks which consists of layernorm, multihead self-attention, residual add, MLP \n",
    "            # creates a list of instances of Block - 1 Block object for each loop of the block layer\n",
    "            h = nn.ModuleList(Block(config) for _ in range(config.n_layer)),\n",
    "            # layernorm layer\n",
    "            ln_f = nn.LayerNorm(config.n_embd)\n",
    "        ))\n",
    "        # since input shape (into block) = output shape (out of block) => shape of (no.examples, block_size, n_embd)\n",
    "        # want to output a prob dist. for the next character, after applying softmax, so we require shape of (no. examples, block_size, vocab_size) \n",
    "        # hence multiply by a layer of shape (n_embd, vocab_size) - linear projection to return the correct output shape\n",
    "        self.lm_head = nn.Linear(config.n_embd, config.vocab_size, bias=False)\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # weight sharing scheme \n",
    "        self.transformer.wte.weight = self.lm_head.weight\n",
    "        # we are making the token embedding matrix's weights be equivalent to the linear projection's (applied at the end of the transformer after the block) weights\n",
    "        # .weight shape of Linear stores in the opposite shape as its constructor (vocab_size, n_embd)\n",
    "        # .weight of embedding stores in the same shape as its constructor (vocab_size, n_embd)\n",
    "        # the shape of the weights are therefore the same and we can therebyb equate them to \"share weights\"\n",
    "        # intuitively however, the main reason why we can equate them (aside from just purely having the same shape) is because of the following: \n",
    "        # if 2 tokens are similar semantically they should have a similar vector in the token embedding space, similarly for these 2 similar tokens, we expect them to have similar probabilities when outputted by the transformer\n",
    "        # since wte tries to embed tokens to vectors and lm_head tries to convert these outputs to logits for each character (scores) which are representative of probabiities when softmaxxed, they intuitively have a similar function so can be equated\n",
    "        # this saves significant time by sharing parameters, decreasing the computations required and making training more efficient (have to train only 1 matrix instead of 2)\n",
    "\n",
    "        # init params \n",
    "        # .apply() is a build-in nn.Module method which when called recursively walks through every submodule of self in the model and applies the function to initialise weights\n",
    "        # A submodule of self is anything where self.something points to an instance of nn.Module or one of its subclasses (e.g. nn.Linear, nn.Embedding, etc.)\n",
    "        # weights are initialised dependeing if its a Linear layer or for embedding\n",
    "        self.apply(self.__init_weights)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # default initialisation\n",
    "    # helps to guarantee that the weights and parameters upon initialisation produce reasonable losses that aren't inflated\n",
    "    # this runs once at model construction time - self.apply(self.__init_weights) walks through every submodule in the model one time cand call the function one ach\n",
    "    def __init_weights(self, module):\n",
    "        if isinstance(module, nn.Linear): # if a Linear module\n",
    "            std = 0.02 \n",
    "            if hasattr(module, 'NANOGPT_SCALE_INIT'): # check if it has the manual tag - we only consider attn and mlp outputs since they are accumulated onto x, other outputs are not involved involved in residual additions to x\n",
    "                std *= (2 * self.config.n_layer) ** -0.5 # if it has the tag then scale down the std by some variable amount (shrink the default 0.02)\n",
    "                # In the residual stream we are adding outputs of the operations attn and mlp, each of which have its own variance, meaning the variances add up\n",
    "                # As we keep adding to x (activations), it becomes larger and larger and if the weights are too large, we get big gradients and unstable training\n",
    "                # The key is therefore to scale down the std of the initial stds of the outputs from attn and mlp so the values sampled for weights from the initial dist. aren't too large \n",
    "            torch.nn.init.normal_(module.weight, mean=0.0, std=std) # initialises the module's weights by randomly sampling values from a normal dist. with mean=0.0 and std scaled down\n",
    "            if module.bias is not None:\n",
    "                torch.nn.init.zeros_(module.bias)\n",
    "        elif isinstance(module, nn.Embedding): # if an embedding module\n",
    "            torch.nn.init.normal_(module.weight, mean=0.0, std=0.02)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "    def forward(self, idx, targets=None): # add targets as an optional parameter to pass labels when we want to calculate loss during training \n",
    "        # idx is shape of (B, T) and represent the tokens produced from tokenisation (split + BPE)\n",
    "        B, T = idx.shape\n",
    "        # T cannot be greater than the blocK_size, that is the maximum length of the context window that we can provide\n",
    "        assert T <= self.config.block_size, f\"Cannot forward sequence length of {T}, block_size is only {self.config.block_size}\"\n",
    "\n",
    "        # forward the token and position embeddings\n",
    "        tok_emb = self.transformer.wte(idx)\n",
    "        pos_emb = self.transformer.wpe(torch.arange(0, T, dtype=torch.long, device=idx.device)) # creates an embedding vector for each of the 0 to T positions in a sequence\n",
    "        x = tok_emb + pos_emb # combines position and token embeddings to get a vector representetive of the meaning and position\n",
    "\n",
    "        # forward the blocks for the transformer\n",
    "        # transformer.h stores all the blocks and we are simply iterating over all the blocks and passing x through them\n",
    "        for block in self.transformer.h:\n",
    "            x = block(x)\n",
    "\n",
    "        # forward the final layernorm and the classifier\n",
    "        x = self.transformer.ln_f(x) \n",
    "        logits = self.lm_head(x) # softmax applied when calculating loss use F.cross_entropy\n",
    "        loss = None \n",
    "        if targets is not None: \n",
    "            # flattens logits and targets from 3D to 2D and 1D respectively to calculate the loss\n",
    "            loss = F.cross_entropy(logits.view(-1, logits.size(-1)), targets.view(-1))\n",
    "            # logits are 3D with a shape of (B, T, vocab_size) after outputted from all the layers of the transformer (softmax is applied inside of F.cross_entropy when calculating the loss)\n",
    "            # We want to flatten it to (B*T, vocab_size) so it becomes a 2D tensor no longer separated by batch\n",
    "            # Our targets were a 2D tensor as well separated by batch (batch, target) and as such we want to flatten this so it can be compared with the logits\n",
    "            # logits dim(0) = targets dim(0) for valid cross_entropy_loss comparison\n",
    "        return logits, loss\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Hyper Parameter Tuning - Weight Decay + FusedAdamW\n",
    "    def configure_optimizers(self, weight_decay, learning_rate, device):\n",
    "        # start with all of the candidate parameters (that require grad) before we split into params that are 2D or larger\n",
    "        param_dict = {pn: p for pn, p in self.named_parameters()}\n",
    "        param_dict = {pn: p for pn, p in param_dict.items() if p.requires_grad}\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # create optim groups. Any parameters that is 2D will be weight decayed, otherwise no.\n",
    "        # i.e. all weight tensors in matmuls + embeddings decay, all biases and layernorms don't.\n",
    "        decay_params = [p for n, p in param_dict.items() if p.dim() >= 2]\n",
    "        nodecay_params = [p for n, p in param_dict.items() if p.dim() < 2]\n",
    "        optim_groups = [\n",
    "            {'params': decay_params, 'weight_decay': weight_decay},\n",
    "            {'params': nodecay_params, 'weight_decay': 0.0}\n",
    "        ] # stores a list of 2 dicts with params and weight decay keys\n",
    "\n",
    "        # find no_ parameters being decayed and not being decayed\n",
    "        num_decay_params = sum(p.numel() for p in decay_params) # get numel() for each parameter in decay_params and sum the number of elements for each param to get total no. parameters\n",
    "        num_nodecay_params = sum(p.numel() for p in nodecay_params)\n",
    "        print(f\"num decayed parameter tensors: {len(decay_params)}, with {num_decay_params:,} parameters\")\n",
    "        print(f\"num non-decayed parameter tensors: {len(nodecay_params)}, with {num_nodecay_params:,} parameters\")\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # Create AdamW optimizer and use the fused version if it is available\n",
    "        fused_available = 'fused' in inspect.signature(torch.optim.AdamW).parameters # checks if the installed PyTorch version's AdamW supports the 'fused' argument, to avoid crashing on older versions that don't\n",
    "        use_fused = fused_available and device == \"cuda\"\n",
    "        optimizer = torch.optim.AdamW(params=optim_groups, lr=learning_rate, betas=(0.9, 0.95), eps=1e-8, fused=use_fused)\n",
    "        # we can pass in a list of dictionaries consisting of the params and the corresponding weight_decay to params as an argument\n",
    "        # torch.optim.AdamW will automatically process the required weight decays\n",
    "        # on every optimizer.step() call for a decay-group parameter the update is weight = weight - lr * gradient_update - lr * weight_decay * weight\n",
    "        return optimizer\n",
    "    "
   ]
  },
