   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "33de815c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### **Efficiency Techniques**\n",
    "\n",
    "Starting point: 1000ms per training step (no optimizations)\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "**1. Tensor Cores / TF32 precision**\n",
    "\n",
    "- First optimization applied. 1000ms → 333ms\n",
    "- Tensor Cores are specialised GPU hardware units for fast matrix multiplication\n",
    "- TF32 (TensorFloat-32) lets float32 matmuls run on tensor cores by truncating the mantissa (less precision, same exponent range as float32) — minimal accuracy loss, real speedup\n",
    "- Enabled with a single global setting, no architecture changes needed\n",
    "\n",
    "    ```python\n",
    "    torch.set_float32_matmul_precision('high')  # enables TF32 for matmuls on supported GPUs\n",
    "    ```\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "**2. float16 / bfloat16 (mixed precision via autocast)**\n",
    "\n",
    "- Second optimization applied. 333ms → 300ms\n",
    "- Covers gradient scalers (needed for float16, since its smaller exponent range risks overflow/underflow) and bfloat16 (bf16), which has the same exponent range as float32 (no scaler needed) but less precision (mantissa)\n",
    "- bf16 is generally preferred on modern hardware since it avoids the extra gradient-scaling complexity float16 requires\n",
    "- Applied via `torch.autocast`, which runs eligible operations in lower precision automatically, leaving sensitive ops in float32\n",
    "\n",
    "    ```python\n",
    "    with torch.autocast(device_type=device, dtype=torch.bfloat16):\n",
    "        logits, loss = model(x, y)\n",
    "    ```\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "**3. torch.compile**\n",
    "\n",
    "- Third optimization applied. 300ms → 130ms (largest single speedup in the whole section)\n",
    "- JIT-compiles the model, analysing the full computation graph and fusing multiple operations into fewer, more efficient GPU kernels\n",
    "- Addresses \"Python overhead\" — without it, PyTorch executes operations eagerly, one at a time, each with its own memory round-trip\n",
    "- Single line, no changes to model logic required\n",
    "\n",
    "    ```python\n",
    "    model = GPT(config)\n",
    "    model = torch.compile(model)\n",
    "    ```\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "**4. Flash Attention**\n",
    "\n",
    "- Fourth optimization applied. 130ms → 96ms\n",
    "- Standard attention materialises the full `(T, T)` score matrix in slow GPU memory (HBM) — a major memory read/write bottleneck, not just a compute one\n",
    "- Flash Attention fuses the attention computation to avoid ever fully materialising that matrix, keeping computation in fast on-chip memory (SRAM) instead\n",
    "- Same mathematical result as manual attention, but far fewer memory reads/writes\n",
    "- Notably, `torch.compile` alone did NOT find this optimization automatically — it had to be applied explicitly, replacing the manual Q/K/V → scores → mask → softmax → @V steps with one fused call\n",
    "\n",
    "    ```python\n",
    "    # Replaces the manual implementation:\n",
    "    # att = (q @ k.transpose(-2,-1)) * (1.0 / math.sqrt(k.size(-1)))\n",
    "    # att = att.masked_fill(self.bias[:,:,:T,:T] == 0, float('-inf'))\n",
    "    # att = F.softmax(att, dim=-1)\n",
    "    # y = att @ v\n",
    "\n",
    "    y = F.scaled_dot_product_attention(q, k, v, is_causal=True)  # flash attention under the hood\n",
    "    ```\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "**5. Nice / Ugly Numbers**\n",
    "\n",
    "- Fifth and final optimization in this section. 96ms → 93ms\n",
    "- GPU kernels are heavily optimised for tensor dimensions that are powers of 2 (or have many factors of 2) — \"nice\" numbers. \"Ugly\" numbers (odd sizes, large prime factors) fall into slower code paths\n",
    "- GPT-2's real vocab_size is 50257 — an \"ugly\" number\n",
    "- Padding it up to 50304 (divisible by many powers of 2) wastes a small amount of extra parameter space (unused vocab rows, never trained on since they never appear in data) but lets the GPU use its fastest kernels — net speedup despite doing \"more\" work on paper\n",
    "\n",
    "    ```python\n",
    "    # Ugly: 50257 (GPT-2's real vocab size)\n",
    "    # Nice: 50304 (padded up, divisible by 128)\n",
    "    config.vocab_size = 50304\n",
    "    ```\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "**Summary of the timing progression (as reported in the video):**\n",
    "\n",
    "| Step | Optimization | Time |\n",
    "|---|---|---|\n",
    "| Start | none | 1000ms |\n",
    "| 1 | TF32 (Tensor Cores) | 333ms |\n",
    "| 2 | bfloat16 mixed precision | 300ms |\n",
    "| 3 | torch.compile | 130ms |\n",
    "| 4 | Flash Attention | 96ms |\n",
    "| 5 | Nice numbers (vocab padding) | 93ms |"
   ]
  },
