  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2263b48e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### **Tuning HyperParameters**\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "Follows guidance from the GPT-2 and GPT-3 papers (OpenAI never published GPT-2's exact training hyperparameters, so GPT-3's paper is used to fill the gaps, since it documents these choices in more detail).\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "**1. AdamW optimizer**\n",
    "\n",
    "- The optimizer used, instead of plain SGD — adapts the learning rate per-parameter using running estimates of gradient mean and variance, plus decoupled weight decay (the \"W\" in AdamW)\n",
    "- Specific betas used, per GPT-3 paper guidance: `beta1 ≈ 0.9`, `beta2 ≈ 0.95` (note: PyTorch's default beta2 is 0.999 — this is deliberately changed to match GPT-3's setup)\n",
    "- `epsilon ≈ 1e-8` (small constant for numerical stability, avoids division by zero)\n",
    "\n",
    "    ```python\n",
    "    optimizer = torch.optim.AdamW(model.parameters(), lr=..., betas=(0.9, 0.95), eps=1e-8)\n",
    "    ```\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "**2. Gradient Clipping**\n",
    "\n",
    "- Covered in the same section as AdamW setup — caps the global norm of all gradients at a max value (1.0) to prevent destructively large updates from occasional gradient spikes\n",
    "- (This is the `clip_grad_norm_` line from before — global norm = sqrt of sum of squares of all gradients across the whole model, rescaled down only if it exceeds the max)\n",
    "\n",
    "    ```python\n",
    "    norm = torch.nn.utils.clip_grad_norm_(model.parameters(), 1.0)\n",
    "    ```\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "**3. Learning Rate Scheduler — warmup + cosine decay**\n",
    "\n",
    "- Learning rate starts near zero, linearly increases (warmup) over a set number of steps, then decays following a cosine curve down to a minimum value\n",
    "- Warmup prevents large, destabilizing updates early in training when the model's weights are still essentially random\n",
    "- Cosine decay smoothly reduces the learning rate over the rest of training, rather than dropping it abruptly\n",
    "\n",
    "    ```python\n",
    "    def get_lr(step):\n",
    "        if step < warmup_steps:\n",
    "            return max_lr * (step + 1) / warmup_steps\n",
    "        if step > max_steps:\n",
    "            return min_lr\n",
    "        decay_ratio = (step - warmup_steps) / (max_steps - warmup_steps)\n",
    "        coeff = 0.5 * (1.0 + math.cos(math.pi * decay_ratio))\n",
    "        return min_lr + coeff * (max_lr - min_lr)\n",
    "    ```\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "**4. Weight Decay, FusedAdamW**\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Weight decay:** only applied to weights that participate in matrix multiplications and embeddings (2D+ parameter tensors) because those are the large computational weight matrices at risk of overfitting by relying too heavily on a few oversied values (1D parameters are small per-channel adjustments with no equivalent overfitting risk)\n",
    "\n",
    "- Discourages the model's weights from growing arbitrarily large which helps prevent overfitting. Mechanically it adds a small penalty to the loss that pushes every weight slightly toward 0 at each training step, in proportion to the weight's current size. This encourages the network to spread useful information across many weights more evenly, preventing large weights\n",
    "\n",
    "- **FusedAdamW:** a fused-kernel version of AdamW available in newer PyTorch versions — optimizes memory movement and computation on the GPU, giving a speed improvement (part of what drops timing to 90ms in this section) - A more computationally efficient AdamW that implements the same algorithm\n",
    "\n",
    "    ```python\n",
    "    # Hyper Parameter Tuning - Weight Decay + FusedAdamW\n",
    "    def configure_optimizers(self, weight_decay, learning_rate, device_type):\n",
    "        # start with all of the candidate parameters (that require grad) before we split into params that are 2D or larger\n",
    "        param_dict = {pn: p for pn, p in self.named_parameters()}\n",
    "        param_dict = {pn: p for pn, p in param_dict.items() if p.requires_grad}\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # create optim groups. Any parameters that is 2D will be weight decayed, otherwise no.\n",
    "        # i.e. all weight tensors in matmuls + embeddings decay, all biases and layernorms don't.\n",
    "        decay_params = [p for n, p in param_dict.items() if p.dim() >= 2]\n",
    "        nodecay_params = [p for n, p in param_dict.items() if p.dim() < 2]\n",
    "        optim_groups = [\n",
    "            {'params': decay_params, 'weight_decay': weight_decay},\n",
    "            {'params': nodecay_params, 'weight_decay': 0.0}\n",
    "        ] # stores a list of 2 dicts with params and weight decay keys\n",
    "\n",
    "        # find no_ parameters being decayed and not being decayed\n",
    "        num_decay_params = sum(p.numel() for p in decay_params) # get numel() for each parameter in decay_params and sum the number of elemebts for each param to get total no. parameters\n",
    "        num_nodecay_params = sum(p.numel() for p in nodecay_params)\n",
    "        print(f\"num decayed parameter tensors: {len(decay_params)}, with {num_decay_params:,} parameters\")\n",
    "        print(f\"num non-decayed parameter tensors: {len(nodecay_params)}, with {num_nodecay_params:,} parameters\")\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # Create AdamW optimizer and use the fused version if it is available\n",
    "        fused_available = 'fused' in inspect.signature(torch.optim.AdamW).parameters\n",
    "        use_fused = fused_available and device_type == \"cuda\"\n",
    "        optimizer = torch.optim.AdamW(optim_groups, lr=learning_rate, betas=(0.9, 0.95), eps=1e-8, fused=use_fused)\n",
    "        # we can pass in a list of dictionaries consisting of the params and the corresponding weight_decay to params as an argument\n",
    "        # torch.optim.AdamW will automatically process the required weight decays\n",
    "        return optimizer\n",
    "    ```\n",
    "\n",
    "- For every `optimizer.step()` that occurs, the weights are decayed according to the following formula - `weight = weight - lr * gradient_update - lr * weight_decay * weight`\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "**5. Gradient Accumulation**\n",
    "\n",
    "- GPT-3's paper specifies a very large effective batch size (~500,000 tokens) that can't fit in GPU memory for a single forward/backward pass -- gradient accumulation simulates it without needing that much memory at once\n",
    "- Split the target effective batch into smaller micro-batches; run each micro-batch's forward + backward pass sequentially, without calling `optimizer.step()` or `zero_grad()` in between\n",
    "- Each micro-batch's loss is divided by `grad_accum_steps` before `.backward()` -- since `.grad` accumulates (+=) rather than overwrites across calls, this turns the accumulated sum into the correct average gradient across all micro-batches, not an inflated raw sum\n",
    "\n",
    "- Only call `optimizer.step()` once all micro-batches are accumulated -- one parameter update per effective batch, mathematically equivalent to running the full large batch \n",
    "in a single pass\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Microbatching (Gradient Accumulation) Summary:** when a full batch is too large to fit in GPU VRAM, it is split into smaller microbatches — each microbatch computes its own loss (divided by the number of microbatches to weight its contribution correctly), calls `.backward()` to accumulate gradients, then once all microbatches are processed the optimizer `.step()` is called once using the fully accumulated gradient — mathematically equivalent to training on the full batch in one go, just with lower peak memory usage\n",
    "\n",
    "- Lets you match large-batch training behavior on hardware that can't fit the full batch at once\n",
    "\n",
    "    ```python\n",
    "    for micro_step in range(grad_accum_steps):\n",
    "        x, y = train_loader.next_batch()\n",
    "        logits, loss = model(x, y)\n",
    "        loss = loss / grad_accum_steps  # scale down since gradients accumulate (sum) by default\n",
    "        loss.backward()\n",
    "    optimizer.step()\n",
    "    optimizer.zero_grad()\n",
    "    ```\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "**6. Distributed Data Parallel (DDP)**\n",
    "\n",
    "- Splits training across multiple GPUs — each GPU processes a different slice of the batch simultaneously, computing its own forward/backward pass independently\n",
    "- Gradients are then synchronized (averaged) across all GPUs before the optimizer step, so every GPU's copy of the model stays identical/in sync\n",
    "- Launched via `torchrun`, requires wrapping the model in `DDP(...)` and handling rank/world_size/device assignment per process\n",
    "\n",
    "    ```python\n",
    "    from torch.nn.parallel import DistributedDataParallel as DDP\n",
    "    from torch.distributed import init_process_group, destroy_process_group\n",
    "    import torch.distributed as dist\n",
    "    # set up DDP (distributed data parallel).\n",
    "    # torchrun command sets the env variables RANK, LOCAL_RANK, and WORLD_SIZE\n",
    "    ddp = int(os.environ.get('RANK', -1)) != -1 # is this a ddp run?\n",
    "    if ddp:\n",
    "        # use of DDP atm demands CUDA, we set the device appropriately according to rank\n",
    "        assert torch.cuda.is_available(), \"for now i think we need CUDA for DDP\"\n",
    "        init_process_group(backend='nccl')\n",
    "        ddp_rank = int(os.environ['RANK'])\n",
    "        ddp_local_rank = int(os.environ['LOCAL_RANK'])\n",
    "        ddp_world_size = int(os.environ['WORLD_SIZE'])\n",
    "        device = f'cuda:{ddp_local_rank}'\n",
    "        torch.cuda.set_device(device)\n",
    "        master_process = ddp_rank == 0 # this process will do logging, checkpointing etc.\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        # vanilla, non-DDP run\n",
    "        ddp_rank = 0\n",
    "        ddp_local_rank = 0\n",
    "        ddp_world_size = 1\n",
    "        master_process = True\n",
    "        # attempt to autodetect device\n",
    "        device = \"cpu\"\n",
    "        if torch.cuda.is_available():\n",
    "            device = \"cuda\"\n",
    "        elif hasattr(torch.backends, \"mps\") and torch.backends.mps.is_available():\n",
    "            device = \"mps\"\n",
    "        print(f\"using device: {device}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    # added after video, pytorch can be serious about it's device vs. device_type distinction\n",
    "    device_type = \"cuda\" if device.startswith(\"cuda\") else \"cpu\"\n",
    "    ```\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "**Summary of the progression through this section:**\n",
    "\n",
    "| Step | Topic |\n",
    "|---|---|\n",
    "| 1 | AdamW optimizer (betas, epsilon per GPT-3 paper) |\n",
    "| 2 | Gradient clipping (global norm capped at 1.0) |\n",
    "| 3 | LR scheduler: warmup + cosine decay |\n",
    "| 4 | Batch size schedule, weight decay (selective), FusedAdamW (→ 90ms) |\n",
    "| 5 | Gradient accumulation (simulate large batch sizes on limited memory) |\n",
    "| 6 | Distributed Data Parallel (DDP) — multi-GPU training |\n"
   ]
  },
